  "articleSummary": "The article \"The Priority Trap\" critiques the use of rigid, fixed-priority dropdowns (e.g., P1-P4) in project management tools like Jira, arguing that they create a \"priority inflation\" trap where teams endlessly add new levels (e.g., P0, P00) to accommodate shifting priorities. The core thesis is that **priority is a dynamic, context-dependent concept** that cannot be captured by static labels, leading to bloated backlogs and \"engineering theater.\" The author proposes alternatives like unbounded numerical priorities, multidimensional scoring systems (e.g., MoSCoW, Kano), or dynamic reassessment to better align with evolving business needs. The tone is analytical and cautionary, drawing parallels to the \"z-index war\" in front-end development to highlight the chaos of unbounded prioritization. The intended audience includes software teams, product managers,",
